edu.columbia.stat.wood.pub.sequencememoizer
Class SequenceMemoizerParameters

java.lang.Object
  edu.columbia.stat.wood.pub.sequencememoizer.SequenceMemoizerParameters
Direct Known Subclasses:
IntSequenceMemoizerParameters
public class SequenceMemoizerParameters
extends java.lang.Object

A container object for the parameters of a sequence memoizer. For depths >= discounts.length, the discount is discounts[discounts.length -1]^(alpha ^ (depth - discounts.length + 1)). Alpha is set such that the product of discounts for depths = discounts.length through infinity converges to the specified infinite discount. This prevents the product of the discounts from converging to 0.0 and helps prevent the overdeterminism seen in some other parameterizations of the model.

Author:
nicholasbartlett

Field Detail

discounts

public double[] discounts
Unique discount parameters for depth in [0 , discounts.length).

infiniteDiscount

public double infiniteDiscount
The product of the discounts for depths of discounts.length through infinity will converge to this infinite discount. In more interpretable terms this means that if conditional distribution R is at depth discounts.length-1 then the prior indicates that restaurants at near infinite depth which share the same recent context of length discounts.length-1 will follow a Pitman-Yor distribution centered at R with discount infiniteDiscount and concentration 0.0.

maxSequenceLength

public long maxSequenceLength
This value must be greater than or equal to 1024, but we suggest much higher, probably something like maxNumberRestaurants * 10. The construction of the tree which makes up the major data structure for the model requires that edges index into an underlying sequence. This number provides a maximum allowable length for this underlying sequence. The shortening of this sequence may (likely will) require that some restaurants are deleted from the tree, though if this is set appropriately high and the number of restaurants are limited, it is likely that all of the deletion will happen randomly and not as a result of shortening the underlying sequence.
